  "prompt": "What are the best movies one must watch?",
  "response": "The definition of \"best movies\" can vary widely based on personal taste, but here is a list of acclaimed films across various genres and eras that are often considered must-watch:\n\n### Classics\n1. **The Godfather (1972)** - A masterpiece of American cinema about mafia families and power.\n2. **Casablanca (1942)** - A romantic drama set against the backdrop of World War II.\n3. **Citizen Kane (1941)** - Often cited as the greatest film of all time, it explores ambition and loss.\n\n### Drama\n1. **Forrest Gump (1994)** - A touching story of a man's life journey through significant historical events.\n2. **12 Angry Men (1957)** - A tense courtroom drama focusing on deliberation and justice.\n3. **Schindler's List (1993)** - A harrowing depiction of the Holocaust and one man's efforts to save lives.\n\n### Action/Thriller\n1. **Pulp Fiction (1994)** - An innovative crime drama known for its unique storytelling structure.\n2. **Die Hard (1988)** - A quintessential action film that set the standard for the genre.\n3. **Mad Max: Fury Road (2015)** - A high-octane, visually stunning revival of the post-apocalyptic action genre.\n\n### Science Fiction/Fantasy\n1. **2001: A Space Odyssey (1968)** - A groundbreaking film exploring humanity and technology.\n2. **Star Wars: Episode IV \u2013 A New Hope (1977)** - A cultural phenomenon that reshaped the sci-fi genre.\n3. **The Lord of the Rings Trilogy (2001-2003)** - An epic adaptation of Tolkien's books showcasing friendship and bravery.\n\n### Animation\n1. **Spirited Away (2001)** - A beautifully animated film by Hayao Miyazaki that captivates audiences of all ages.\n2. **Toy Story (1995)** - The first entirely computer-animated feature film, it redefined animation storytelling.\n3. **Into the Spider-Verse (2018)** - An innovative and visually stunning take on the Spider-Man franchise.\n\n### Comedy\n1. **Monty Python and the Holy Grail (1975)** - A cult classic filled with absurd humor and clever satire.\n2. **Groundhog Day (1993)** - A unique comedy with a philosophical twist about reliving the same day.\n3. **The Big Lebowski (1998)** - A quirky film that has developed a devoted fan base for its eccentric characters and dialogue.\n\n### Horror\n1. **Psycho (1960)** - Alfred Hitchcock's classic thriller that set new standards for horror cinema.\n2. **Get Out (2017)** - A contemporary horror film that cleverly tackles social issues.\n3. **The Shining (1980)** - Stanley Kubrick\u2019s chilling adaptation of Stephen King\u2019s novel.\n\n### International Cinema\n1. **Parasite (2019)** - A genre-bending South Korean film that critiques class disparity.\n2. **Pan's Labyrinth (2006)** - A dark fantasy film by Guillermo del Toro set against the backdrop of post-Civil War Spain.\n3. **City of God (2002)** - A powerful drama depicting the rise of organized crime in the favelas of Rio de Janeiro.\n\n### Documentaries\n1. **The Act of Killing (2012)** - A chilling exploration of violence and memory through the eyes of former Indonesian death squad leaders.\n2. **Won't You Be My Neighbor? (2018)** - A heartfelt look at Fred Rogers and his impact on American culture.\n3. **13th (2016)** - A thought-provoking examination of race, justice, and mass incarceration in the United States.\n\nThis list is by no means exhaustive, but it offers a diverse mix that represents different genres and filmmaking styles. It's always worth exploring further based on your interests!",
